definition.value: A ceramide that is the N-hexacosanoyl derivative of C20 phytosphingosine.
An amino cyclitol glycoside that is 4alpha,6alpha-diaminocyclohexane-1beta,2alpha,3beta-triol (2-deoxystreptamine) in which the pro-R hydroxy group is substituted by an alpha-D-glucosyl residue.
An organic cation obtained by protonation of the four free amino groups of neamine; major species at pH 7.3.
An organic cation obtained by protonation of the six free amino groups of neomycin C; major species at pH 7.3.
An organophosphate oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate OH groups of isopentenyl phosphate; major species at pH 7.3.
An organophosphate oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate OH groups of trans,polycis-decaprenyl phosphate; major species at pH 7.3.
An organophosphate oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of the diphosphate OH groups of N-acetyl-alpha-D-glucosaminyl-1-diphospho-trans,polycis-decaprenol; major species at pH 7.3.
A 2-oxo monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of 2-oxo-3-(5-oxofuran-2-ylidene)propanoic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
An organic cation obtained by protonation of the four free amino groups and deprotonation of the phosphate OH groups of 5''-phosphoribostamycin; major species at pH 7.3.
A pyridine ring substituted with methyl groups at positions 2 and 4, a hydroxyl at position 3, and a hydroxymethyl group at position 5.
A long-chain aldehyde that is octadecanal in which one of the hydrogens at position 2 is replaced by a hydroxy group.
An organic cation obtained by protonation of the four free amino groups of butirosin B; major species at pH 7.3.
A primary ammonium ion obtained by protonation of the four amino groups and deprotonation of the carboxy group of gamma-L-glutamylbutirosin B; major species at pH 7.3.
An unsaturated fatty acyl-CoA resulting from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of (9Z)-myristoleic acid.
A very long-chain fatty acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of docosanoic (behenic) acid.

A anionic ceramide phosphoinositol compound having a hexacosanoyl group attached to the ceramide nitrogen and no hydroxylation at C-4 of the long-chain base or at C-2 or C-3 of the very-long-chain fatty acid. Major species at pH 7.3
A 1-phosphatidyl-D-myo-inositol in which the acyl group at position 1 is specified as stearoyl (octadecanoyl) while that at position 2 is unspecified.

An anionic ceramide phosphoinositol compound having a tetracosanoyl group attached to the ceramide nitrogen and no hydroxylation at C-4 of the long-chain base, or at C-2 or C-3 of the very-long-chain fatty acid. Major species at pH 7.3.

The sesquihydrate of cyproheptadine hydrochloride. Note that the drug named cyproheptadine hydrochloride generally refers to cyproheptadine hydrochloride sesquihydrate. A sedating antihistamine with antimuscarinic and calcium-channel blocking actions, it is used for the relief of allergic conditions including rhinitis, conjunctivitis due to inhalant allergens and foods, urticaria and angioedema, and in pruritic skin disorders. Unlike other antihistamines, it is also a seratonin receptor antagonist, making it useful in conditions such as vascular headache and anorexia.
The organophosphate oxoanion formed from 1-monolysocardiolipin by deprotonation of the two phospho groups; principal species present at pH 7.3

An anionic ceramide phosphoinositol compound having a hexacosanoyl group attached to the ceramide nitrogen, no hydroxylation at C-4 of the long-chain base, and hydroxylation at C-2 of the very-long-chain fatty acid. Major species at pH 7.3.

An anionic ceramide phosphoinositol compound having a tetracosanoyl group attached to the ceramide nitrogen, no hydroxylation at C-4 of the long-chain base, and hydroxylation at C-2 of the very-long-chain fatty acid. Major species at pH 7.3.
A polyprenyl glycosyl phosphate consisting of beta-D-arabinofuranose attached at the 1-position to trans,octacis-decaprenyl phosphate.
A hydroxy fatty acid anion that is the conjugate base of 2-hydroxypalmitic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
An amino cyclitol glycoside derived from neomycin and consisting of neamine substituted at position 3 by a 3-O-(2-amino-2-deoxy-alpha-D-gluco-hexodialdo-1,5-pyranosyl)-beta-D-ribofuranosyl group.
alpha-Neu5Ac-(2->8)-Neu5Ac in which the configuration at the anomeric carbon atom of the residue at the reducing end is beta.
An Aspidosperma alkaloid with molecular formula C21H24N2O3 found in the roots of Madagascar periwinkle (Catharanthus roseus, formerly known as Vinca rosea).
A polyprenyl glycosyl phosphate consisting of beta-D-erythro-pentofuranosid-2-ulose attached at the 1-position to trans,octacis-decaprenyl phosphate.
A 2-hydroxy fatty acid comprising a C16 straight chain carrying a hydroxy substituent at position 2.
An acyl-CoA(4-) oxoanion arising from deprotonation of the phosphate and diphosphate OH groups of any 3-hydroxy fatty acyl-CoA; major species at pH 7.3.
alpha-Neup5Ac-(2->8)-alpha-Neup5Ac-(2->8)-Neup5Ac in which the sialyl residue at the reducing end has beta anomeric configuration.
A phosphatidylglycerol consisting of cardiolipin lacking one fatty acyl group from the 1 or 1'-position.
A phytoceramide compound having a hexadecanoyl group attached to the nitrogen atom.
A butirosin that is butirosin B in which a gamma-L-glutamyl is attached to the amino group of the (S)-4-amino-2-hydroxybutyrate side-chain.
A family of amino cyclitol glycoside antibiotics produced by Bacillus circulans, bears the unique (S)-4-amino-2-hydroxybutyrate (AHBA) side chain.
A butirosin that consists of neamine in which is substituted at position 2 by a beta-D-ribofuranosyl and at position 4 by an (S)-2-hydroxy-4-aminobutyryl group.
An acyl-CoA(4-) oxoanion arising from deprotonation of the phosphate and diphosphate OH groups of any 3-substituted propionyl-CoA; major species at pH 7.3.
A butirosin that consists of neamine in which is substituted at position 2 by a beta-D-xylofuranosyl and at position 4 by an (S)-2-hydroxy-4-aminobutyryl group.
A glycoside phosphate that is ribostamycin (vistamycin) in which the ribofuranosyl residue is substituted at position 5 by a phosphate group.
A 2-oxo monocarboxylic acid that is pyruvic acid substituted at position 3 by a 5-oxofuran-2-ylidene group.
A 3-oxoacyl-CoA(4-) arising from deprotonation of the phosphate and diphosphate groups of 3-oxoicosanoyl-CoA: major species at pH 7.3.
A polyprenyl glycosyl phosphate consisting of N-acetyl-alpha-D-glucosamine attached at the 1-position to trans,octacis-decaprenyl phosphate.

An organophosphate oxoanion that is the conjugate base of CDP-N,N-dimethylethanolamine, obtained by deprotonation of the diphosphate OH groups and protonation of the tertiary amino group; major species at pH 7.3.
A sphingoid obtained by formal oxidation of the 3-hydroxy group of C20 sphinganine.
A purine ribonucleoside 5'-triphosphate that is ATP in which position 2 on the adenine moiety is substituted by a hydroxy group.
An amino trisaccharide comprised of an 6-sulfated N-acetylglucosamine residue linked beta(1->3) to a galactose residue, which is itself linked beta(1->4) to an N-acetylglucosamine residue.
A monoalkyl phosphate that is isopentenyl alcohol in which the hydroxyl hydrogen is substituted by a phosphate group.
An acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of any 3-substituted propionic acid (R =/= H).
